  "prompt": "How does the Aereo antenna work?",
  "response": "Aereo, which operated from 2012 to 2014, used a unique approach to providing access to over-the-air (OTA) television broadcasts. Here's how their system worked, focusing on the key aspects of their antenna technology:\n\n*   **Tiny Individual Antennas:** Aereo employed a large array of very small, individual antennas at its central facilities. Each subscriber was allocated a dedicated antenna, rather than sharing a larger antenna with other users.\n\n*   **Dedicated Antenna Per Subscriber:** This was the cornerstone of their argument against being classified as a \"cable system.\" Aereo claimed they weren't retransmitting content, but rather providing each user with access to their own, private antenna.\n\n*   **Remote Access and Streaming:** When a user selected a channel, Aereo tuned *that user's specific antenna* to the relevant broadcast frequency. The signal from that antenna was then streamed over the internet to the subscriber's device (computer, tablet, phone, etc.).\n\n*   **Geographic Restrictions:** The system only worked within the local broadcast area where Aereo had its antenna farms.\n\n**In simpler terms:**\n\nImagine a large warehouse filled with thousands of tiny TV antennas. When you sign up for Aereo, you're assigned one of these antennas as \"your own.\" When you want to watch a channel, Aereo tunes *your* antenna to that channel and streams the video to you over the internet.\n\n**Why this was controversial:**\n\nBroadcasters argued that Aereo was essentially rebroadcasting their content without permission and without paying retransmission fees (which cable and satellite providers pay). Aereo maintained that they were simply providing an antenna service, similar to renting an antenna to someone who couldn't get good reception at home.\n\n**The Supreme Court Ruling:**\n\nThe U.S. Supreme Court ultimately ruled against Aereo in 2014, finding that its service was \"substantially similar\" to a cable system and therefore subject to copyright laws. This ruling effectively shut down Aereo.\n",
